Solution 8.15. Contraction may be thought of as multiplication by the constant Kronecker-delta tensor $\delta_{
u}^{\mu}$ . But the Lie derivative of the tensor $\delta_{
u}^{\mu}$ is zero, as we can easily prove in a coordinate frame,$$\mathcal {L}_{\mathbf {x}} (\delta_{
u}^{\mu}) = \delta_{
u , \lambda}^{\mu} \mathbf {x}^{\lambda} + \delta_{\lambda}^{\mu} \mathbf {x}_{, 
u}^{\lambda} - \delta_{
u}^{\lambda} \mathbf {x}_{, \lambda}^{\mu} = 0 + \mathbf {x}_{, 
u}^{\mu} - \mathbf {x}_{, 
u}^{\mu} = 0 ,$$and therefore the contraction operator $\delta_{
u}^{\mu}$ can go on either side of $\mathfrak{L}_{\mathbf{x}}$ .
